Jupyter (Julia / Python / R) NotebooksÂ¶

Notebooks are web pages that allow for code to be run from interactively in the web browser.

I would venture to say that Jupyter is the standard among data scientists using python.

Notebooks are a great way to:

  • Explore data
  • Prototype code
  • Walk people through your work
  • Act as an interactive manual
  • Repeat scatterbrained analyses later on

This is one of the best ways to figure out what your data look like

Map the data to a grid

Wait, how do I do that???

In [6]:
numpy.meshgrid?
In [7]:
bathLat = numpy.unique(bathData['Latitude [deg]'])
bathLong = numpy.unique(bathData['Longitude [deg]'])
mapLong, mapLat = numpy.meshgrid(bathLong,bathLat)
mapDepth = bathData['Depth [m]'].reshape(len(bathLat),len(bathLong))*-3.3
In [8]:
coastLong = []
coastLat = []

for jdx,latDepth in enumerate(mapDepth):
    idx = numpy.where(latDepth<0.0)[0][0]
    coastLat.append(bathLat[jdx])
    coastLong.append(bathLong[idx])

PlotlyÂ¶

Plotly is a visualization tool built with Java Script using D3 (Data Driven Documents). It is basically an interface to a pretty plot maker.

  • View in notebook, or as independent html
  • Cross platform (javascript, python, R, matlab)
  • Just use examples and docs (extremely rich, built with jupyter notebooks)
  • Awesome for playing with visual data
  • Can be slow (lots of data in HTML)
In [11]:
from plotly.offline import download_plotlyjs, init_notebook_mode, plot, iplot
from plotly import tools
import plotly.graph_objs as go

init_notebook_mode(connected=True)

trace = go.Scatter(x=xData,y=sineData,name='Sine')

fig.append_trace(resid,2,1)

fig['layout']['yaxis2'].update(title='Noise')
fig['layout']['xaxis2'].update(title='Rad Angle')

depth = go.Contour(x=bathLong,y=bathLat,z=mapDepth,colorscale='Viridis',
                  contours=dict(start=0,end=10e3,size=100,showlines=False))
newport = go.Scatter(x=[newportCoords[0]],y=[newportCoords[1]],mode='markers',
                     marker=dict(color='red',symbol='circle',size=10),
                    name='Newport')
fish = go.Scatter(x=[newportCoords[0],fishCoords[0]],y=[newportCoords[1],fishCoords[1]],
                    mode='lines',line=dict(color='red'),
                    name='Fish')
line = go.Scatter(x=[fishCoords[0]],y=[fishCoords[1]],mode='markers',
                     marker=dict(color='red',symbol='star',size=10),
                     showlegend=False)
profile = go.Scatter(y=profileDepth,xaxis='x2',yaxis='y2',mode='line',line=dict(color='red'),
                     showlegend=False)
coast = go.Scatter(x=coastLong,y=coastLat,mode='line',line=dict(color='cyan'),showlegend=False)
data = [depth,coast,newport,fish,line,profile]
layout = go.Layout(
    legend=dict(orientation="h"),
    xaxis2=dict(domain=[0.05,0.45],anchor='x2',showticklabels=False),
    yaxis2=dict(domain=[0.55,0.9],anchor='y2',showticklabels=False)
)
fig = go.Figure(data=data,layout=layout)
iplot(fig)
